{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01LLdtjLmEs7s3tyz9EdY3pU","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The controller logs show:\n1. `unable to find real backend for alternative backend demo-canary-echo-80. Deleting.` - The canary-canary ingress's backend (canary-echo) is being deleted from the nginx configuration.\n2. All requests still go to `upstream-default-backend` (404) - the `canary.example.com` host is not being routed.\n\nWait, this is very strange. Both the stable and canary ingresses were synced successfully (\"successfully validated configuration, accepting\"), but:\n- The stable backend (stable-echo) has endpoints (10.244.0.173:5678)\n- The canary backend (canary-echo) also has endpoints (10.244.0.174:5678)\n\nYet nginx can't find the real backend for `demo-canary-echo-80` and `canary.example.com` isn't matching. There's also a separate error about the decoy `canary-alt` ingress trying to merge its backend into a hostname that doesn't exist. Let me check the ingress describe output to understand what's happening with the canary annotations.\n\nThe issue is becoming clearer: the `canary-alt` ingress is marked as a canary route for `canary-alt.example.com`, but there's no primary (non-canary) ingress for that hostname, so the controller can't merge the canary backend. The same problem likely applies to the `canary-canary` ingress for `canary.example.com`.\n\nBut the error message about the missing `demo-canary-echo-80` backend is puzzling—when the controller processes the primary ingress `canary-stable`, it's looking for the canary ingress's backends, and if those backends don't exist or can't be resolved, it fails to merge them.\n\nThe timing seems off: the ingresses were created at 13:54:37, the reload happened at 13:54:39, but when I checked the endpoints at 13:55:19, both were already registered. The controller's last reload was at 13:54:39, which might have been before the endpoints were fully ready, and since then there hasn't been a re-sync triggered by the endpoint watch.\n\nLet me check the actual nginx configuration by accessing the controller pod directly to see if the canary endpoint is even in there, or try forcing a re-sync by updating the ingress resources.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1859,"cache_read_input_tokens":52250,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1859},"output_tokens":40,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"352af56b-dd91-491b-a77b-e91f1eeb9892","uuid":"3e22ae46-ca46-44b3-8235-74fc550976f8","request_id":"req_011Cc5ADqSurmj4EZQavMV55"}
